[3] Indonesai: ban upon urban poultry keeping
Date: Mon, 15 Jan 2007
From: Nati Elkin <nati@poultrymed.com>
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailgeneral.asp?fileid=20070115170319&irec=1>

Govt bans commercial animal husbandry in residence areas
--------------------------------------------------------
The government banned on Monday [15 Jan 2007] the presence of commercial
animal husbandry in residence areas, Elshinta radio station reported. The
decision was made to limit the spreading of bird flu virus, which has
claimed 4 lives in Jakarta last week. The radio station stated that the
government would ask the local government to issue bylaw to implement its
decision.
An official from Tangerang regency said that a regency administration would
need one or 2 months to issue a bylaw as an approval from the legislative
council was also required.
--
Nati Elkin
email <nati@poultrymed.com>
[The reemergence of H5N1 during the winter season might be another
indication of the possible though controversial role wild birds may play in
its spread. It will be interesting to follow the data obtained in the
coming weeks by the European Union's H5N1 surveillance in wild birds.
According to the results obtained during 2006 by the said surveillance in
the 14 participating member states, a total of 748 H5N1 infected wild birds
were identified and notified from 1 Feb to 30 Nov 2006. Their occurrence
was restricted to the months February to May 2006. The figures were: Feb
200; Mar 362; Apr 166; May 18; Jun 0; Jul 1; Aug 1; Sep 0; Oct 0; Nov 0.
The ADNS summary report for highly pathogenic avian influenza in wild
birds, including the data pertaining to each state and to each of the 5
bird groups (swans, ducks, geese, birds of prey and "others"), is available
at <http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/adns/adns_wildbirds.pdf>. -
Mod.AS]
